Objective

The objective of this project was to:

Analyze loan customer records
Identify customers with high default risk
Detect early warning signs of delayed EMI payments
Monitor loan portfolio performance
Visualize loan risk trends using dashboards
Dataset Description

A simulated loan dataset was used containing approximately 8,000 customer records.

The dataset includes the following fields:

Customer_ID – Unique ID assigned to each customer
Income – Monthly income of customer
Loan_Amount – Total loan amount taken
Loan_Type – Type of loan (Home, Personal, Auto)
EMI_Amount – Monthly EMI payment
Delay_Days – Number of days EMI payment was delayed
Default_Flag – Indicates default status (1 = Default, 0 = No Default)
Data Cleaning

Before performing analysis, the dataset was cleaned to ensure data quality.

The following steps were performed:

Removed duplicate customer records
Checked for missing or invalid values
Converted numeric fields into proper data types
Standardized loan type names
Filtered records with invalid loan amounts

Example Python operations performed:

df = df.drop_duplicates()

df['Income'] = df['Income'].astype(int)

df['Loan_Type'] = df['Loan_Type'].str.strip()

df = df[df['Loan_Amount'] > 0]
Data Analysis

Several analysis steps were performed to identify loan risk patterns.

Loan Distribution Analysis

Loan types were analyzed to understand the distribution of loans across customers.

Example SQL Query:

SELECT Loan_Type,
COUNT(*) AS Total_Customers
FROM Loan_Data
GROUP BY Loan_Type;

This helped identify the most commonly used loan types.

Default Risk Identification

Customers with delayed EMI payments were identified as potential high-risk customers.

Example SQL Query:

SELECT *
FROM Loan_Data
WHERE Delay_Days > 30;

This helped detect customers who showed early warning signs of default.

Loan-to-Income Ratio Analysis

Loan affordability was analyzed using income and loan amount values.

Example Python:

df['Loan_to_Income_Ratio'] = df['Loan_Amount'] / df['Income']

This helped identify customers who had higher financial burden.

Default Rate Calculation

Default percentage was calculated to measure overall loan risk.

Example SQL:

SELECT
COUNT(CASE WHEN Default_Flag = 1 THEN 1 END) * 100.0
/ COUNT(*) AS Default_Rate
FROM Loan_Data;
Power BI Dashboard

A Power BI dashboard was created to visualize loan portfolio performance.

The dashboard includes:

Total Loan Customers
Total Default Customers
Default Rate (%)
Loan Type Distribution
Default by Loan Type
Delay Days Analysis
Income vs Loan Amount Analysis
High-Risk Customer Identification

These visualizations helped in understanding loan behavior and identifying risky customers.

Key Insights

From the analysis, the following insights were identified:

Personal loans showed a higher default rate compared to other loan types
Customers with Delay Days greater than 30 were more likely to default
Customers with lower income and higher loan amounts had higher risk
High loan-to-income ratio indicated possible financial stress
Loan distribution showed majority customers under home loan category
Business Impact

This project helps financial institutions to:

Identify risky customers early
Reduce loan default rates
Improve loan approval decisions
Monitor loan portfolio risk
Take preventive actions for delayed payments
Tools Used
Python (Pandas) – Data cleaning and analysis
SQL – Data querying and aggregation
Power BI – Dashboard visualization
CSV Dataset – Data storage